    {"intent_id": "compare_sql_nosql", "query": "Compare SQL and NoSQL databases",
     "response": "SQL databases (PostgreSQL, MySQL) use structured tables with predefined schemas, enforce ACID transactions, and excel at complex joins and queries. They scale vertically and are ideal for structured, relational data. NoSQL databases (MongoDB, Redis, Cassandra) use flexible schemas (document, key-value, column-family, or graph models), prioritize horizontal scalability, and often follow BASE (Basically Available, Soft state, Eventually consistent). NoSQL shines with unstructured data, rapid iteration, and massive scale. Choose SQL when data integrity and complex queries matter; choose NoSQL when flexibility, speed, and horizontal scaling are priorities."},
    {"intent_id": "compare_rest_graphql", "query": "Compare REST and GraphQL APIs",
     "response": "REST uses fixed endpoints (GET /users, POST /orders) where each returns a predetermined data shape, often leading to over-fetching or under-fetching. GraphQL provides a single endpoint where clients specify exactly what data they need via queries, reducing network overhead. REST relies on HTTP methods for semantics and is well-cached by CDNs. GraphQL uses POST for everything, making caching harder but offering real-time subscriptions and strong typing via schemas. REST is simpler to set up and widely understood. GraphQL excels when clients have diverse data needs, like mobile apps needing minimal payloads."},
    {"intent_id": "compare_tcp_udp", "query": "Compare TCP and UDP protocols",
     "response": "TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) is connection-oriented, guaranteeing ordered, reliable delivery with error checking, flow control, and congestion management. It uses a three-way handshake to establish connections. UDP (User Datagram Protocol) is connectionless, sending packets without delivery guarantees — no ordering, no retransmission, no handshake. TCP is used for web browsing, email, and file transfer where reliability matters. UDP is used for video streaming, gaming, DNS lookups, and VoIP where speed and low latency outweigh occasional packet loss. TCP has higher overhead; UDP has lower latency."},
    {"intent_id": "compare_docker_vm", "query": "Compare Docker containers and virtual machines",
     "response": "Virtual machines (VMs) run a full guest OS on a hypervisor, providing complete isolation but consuming significant resources (GB of RAM per VM, minutes to boot). Docker containers share the host OS kernel, packaging only the application and its dependencies. Containers start in seconds, use MB of memory, and run many more instances per host. VMs offer stronger security isolation since they have separate kernels. Containers are ideal for microservices, CI/CD pipelines, and rapid scaling. VMs suit workloads needing different OS types or maximum security isolation. Both can complement each other in production environments."},

