    {"intent_id": "explain_photosynthesis", "query": "Explain how photosynthesis works in detail",
     "response": "Photosynthesis converts light energy into chemical energy in two stages. In the light-dependent reactions (in thylakoid membranes), chlorophyll absorbs sunlight and uses it to split water molecules into oxygen, protons, and electrons. The electron transport chain generates ATP and NADPH. In the light-independent reactions (Calvin cycle, in the stroma), the enzyme RuBisCO fixes CO2 into a 3-carbon molecule. Using ATP and NADPH from stage one, this is reduced to G3P, which combines to form glucose. The overall equation: 6CO2 + 6H2O + light energy → C6H12O6 + 6O2. Temperature, light intensity, and CO2 concentration all affect the rate."},
    {"intent_id": "explain_gravity", "query": "Explain how gravity works",
     "response": "In Newtonian physics, gravity is a force between any two masses proportional to their product and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them (F = Gm1m2/r²). Einstein's general relativity reframes gravity as the curvature of spacetime caused by mass and energy. Massive objects like Earth warp the fabric of spacetime, and other objects follow curved paths (geodesics) through this warped geometry — what we perceive as gravitational attraction. This explains phenomena Newton couldn't: gravitational lensing, time dilation near massive objects, and gravitational waves. On Earth, gravity accelerates objects at approximately 9.8 m/s²."},
    {"intent_id": "explain_evolution", "query": "Describe how evolution by natural selection works",
     "response": "Evolution by natural selection operates through four key mechanisms. First, variation exists within populations due to genetic mutations and recombination. Second, organisms produce more offspring than can survive (overproduction). Third, individuals with traits better suited to their environment are more likely to survive and reproduce (differential survival). Fourth, these advantageous traits are heritable and passed to offspring. Over generations, favorable traits become more common in the population (adaptation). Additional mechanisms include genetic drift (random changes in small populations), gene flow (migration between populations), and sexual selection. Speciation occurs when populations become reproductively isolated and diverge sufficiently."},

