    {"intent_id": "debug_cors", "query": "How do I fix CORS errors?",
     "response": "CORS errors occur when a browser blocks requests from one origin to another due to missing Access-Control-Allow-Origin headers. To fix: on your server, add the header 'Access-Control-Allow-Origin' with the requesting domain (or '*' for development). For preflight requests (OPTIONS), also set 'Access-Control-Allow-Methods' (GET, POST, etc.) and 'Access-Control-Allow-Headers' (Content-Type, Authorization). In Express.js, use the 'cors' middleware. In FastAPI, add CORSMiddleware. In Django, use django-cors-headers. For credentials (cookies), set 'Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true' and specify exact origins (not '*'). Never use '*' in production with credentials."},
    {"intent_id": "debug_memory_leak", "query": "How do I find memory leaks in my application?",
     "response": "Start by monitoring memory usage over time with tools like htop, Activity Monitor, or application-level metrics. In Python, use tracemalloc to snapshot memory allocations and compare snapshots to find growth. The objgraph library visualizes object reference graphs. In JavaScript, Chrome DevTools' Memory tab offers heap snapshots and allocation timelines — take snapshots before and after operations, then compare retained sizes. Common causes: unbounded caches, event listener accumulation, circular references, global variable growth, and unclosed connections. Fix by implementing proper cleanup (context managers, removeEventListener), using weak references where appropriate, and setting cache size limits."},
    {"intent_id": "debug_slow_query", "query": "How do I optimize slow database queries?",
     "response": "First, use EXPLAIN ANALYZE to see the query execution plan and identify full table scans, missing indexes, or inefficient joins. Add indexes on columns used in WHERE, JOIN, and ORDER BY clauses. Avoid SELECT * — fetch only needed columns. Use pagination (LIMIT/OFFSET or cursor-based) instead of loading entire result sets. For N+1 query problems, use JOINs or batch loading. Consider denormalization for read-heavy workloads. Add query result caching with Redis for frequently accessed data. Monitor slow query logs and set up alerts. For complex analytical queries, consider materialized views or moving to a data warehouse."},

