    {"intent_id": "arch_microservices", "query": "Explain microservices architecture",
     "response": "Microservices architecture decomposes an application into small, independently deployable services, each owning its own data and business logic. Services communicate via APIs (REST, gRPC) or message queues (RabbitMQ, Kafka). Each service can be developed, tested, deployed, and scaled independently by different teams using different technologies. Benefits include fault isolation, independent scaling, and technology flexibility. Challenges include distributed system complexity, data consistency across services, network latency, and operational overhead. Key patterns: API Gateway for routing, service discovery for location, circuit breakers for fault tolerance, and saga pattern for distributed transactions."},
    {"intent_id": "arch_event_driven", "query": "Describe event-driven architecture",
     "response": "Event-driven architecture (EDA) structures applications around the production, detection, and reaction to events. Producers emit events (state changes) to a message broker (Kafka, RabbitMQ, AWS SNS). Consumers subscribe to event streams and react asynchronously. Key patterns include Event Sourcing (storing state changes as a sequence of events), CQRS (separating read and write models), and pub/sub (decoupling producers from consumers). Benefits: loose coupling, scalability, real-time processing, and natural audit trails. Challenges: eventual consistency, event ordering, debugging distributed flows, and schema evolution. EDA excels in systems requiring real-time reactions and high throughput."},

