    {"intent_id": "explain_load_balancing", "query": "Explain how load balancing works",
     "response": "Load balancing distributes incoming traffic across multiple servers to ensure no single server becomes overwhelmed. A load balancer sits between clients and backend servers, routing requests using algorithms: Round Robin (sequential rotation), Least Connections (sends to server with fewest active connections), Weighted (assigns based on server capacity), IP Hash (same client always reaches same server for session persistence). Layer 4 load balancers route based on IP/port (faster). Layer 7 load balancers inspect HTTP content for smarter routing (path-based, header-based). Health checks continuously verify server availability. Popular tools: Nginx, HAProxy, AWS ALB, Cloudflare. Load balancers also enable zero-downtime deployments and horizontal scaling."},

    # ── LANGUAGE FEATURES (detailed) ──────────────────────────────────
    {"intent_id": "explain_typescript", "query": "Explain the benefits of TypeScript",
     "response": "TypeScript adds static type checking to JavaScript, catching errors at compile time instead of runtime. It provides interfaces and type aliases for defining data shapes, generics for reusable typed components, and enums for named constants. IDE support improves dramatically — autocomplete, refactoring, and inline documentation become precise. TypeScript supports union types (string | number), intersection types, conditional types, and utility types (Partial, Pick, Omit). It compiles to JavaScript, so it runs everywhere JS does. Large codebases benefit most: types serve as documentation, refactoring is safer, and onboarding is faster. Configuration via tsconfig.json controls strictness levels."},
    {"intent_id": "explain_rust_ownership", "query": "Explain Rust's ownership system",
     "response": "Rust's ownership system manages memory without garbage collection through three rules: each value has exactly one owner, only one owner at a time, and when the owner goes out of scope the value is dropped. Borrowing allows temporary references: immutable borrows (&T, unlimited simultaneous) and mutable borrows (&mut T, exclusive). The borrow checker enforces these at compile time, preventing data races, dangling pointers, and use-after-free bugs. Lifetimes annotate how long references are valid. Move semantics transfer ownership instead of copying. This system provides memory safety and thread safety with zero runtime cost, making Rust ideal for systems programming, WebAssembly, and performance-critical applications."},

