    {"intent_id": "explain_cookies_sessions", "query": "Explain how cookies and sessions work",
     "response": "Cookies are small pieces of data stored in the browser and sent with every HTTP request to the same domain. The server sets cookies via the Set-Cookie header with attributes: Domain, Path, Expires/Max-Age, Secure (HTTPS only), HttpOnly (no JavaScript access), and SameSite (CSRF protection). Sessions use cookies to store a session ID that maps to server-side data (in memory, Redis, or a database). When a user logs in, the server creates a session, stores user data server-side, and sends the session ID as a cookie. On each request, the server looks up the session ID to retrieve user state. Sessions are more secure since sensitive data stays server-side."},
